For the reader who has read Chapters 1-4 straight through: rest. When you come back, Chapter 5 opens the runtime layer. Environments, macros, reader. Denser reading. Same reflexes.

For the reader who is skimming: go back and do the exercises. Introspection is a reflex; reflexes require practice.

Onward to Chapter 5, where the runtime layer opens up and environments become walkable data structures — the foundation on which closures, lexical scope, and every binding you have ever created rest.

The introspection reflex you built in Part One will carry you into Part Two. Trust the reflex. Type the examples. Turn the page.

Chapter 5 awaits with a walkable representation of Scheme's lexical scope model and the introspection verbs that turn frames and closures into inspectable data structures you can query one prompt at a time, without any external tooling required or any special debug mode ever enabled.
